{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016wwQES8iqkFu6qwBv54nLF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: The primary translator produces a grammatically coherent translation that preserves the meaning of the source text, not just a word-for-word substitution.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about translation quality — whether the neural MT API produces coherent, meaning-preserving translations. This is inherently about what the model produces.\n- REAL-INFRA: The neural MT API is an external service. Could a stub reproduce this? No — a stub always returns a canned response. The actual quality of translation can only be evaluated with the real model.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes — this directly tests the output quality of a neural machine translation model. Whether the translation is grammatically coherent and preserves meaning depends entirely on the real model's output. A mock/stub would just return a constant, hiding any real failure.\n\n\n- MULTI-STEP: No multi-step agentic pipeline.\n\nMinimum level: **Agentic** — correctness depends on real neural MT model output quality.\n\n**Behavior 2: When the translation API returns a 503 error, the service transparently falls back to the dictionary-based translator without returning an error to the caller.**\n\nThis tests the fallback logic across multiple modules: the API client, error handling, and the dictionary translator. We can stub the translation API to return a 503 and verify the fallback behavior without needing real HTTP infrastructure.\n\nThe key question is whether the service correctly routes to the fallback when the primary API fails—this is about orchestration and error handling, not translation quality, so a stubbed 503 response is sufficient to validate the path. We don't need real network calls or OS-level failures to test this routing logic.\n\nFor the dictionary fallback behavior, I'm checking whether it retrieves the right pre-stored translation from SQLite when a phrase exists in the database. Since SQLite is local, I can use an in-memory or file-based instance to test the boundary between the fallback translator and the database without needing real infrastructure.\n\nThe key question is whether to mock SQLite or use a real one — mocking could hide bugs in the query logic, so I should use an actual SQLite instance. Even though the lookup itself is deterministic, the interaction between the application code and the database makes this an Integration-level test rather than Unit.\n\nFor the quality tracking behavior, I'm seeing two distinct concerns: the edit distance computation is a pure algorithm (Unit level), but storing the metric involves persistence (Integration level). Since the behavior requires both parts to work correctly together, this lands at Integration level. The behavior explicitly bundles computation and storage together, so Integration is the right level to test the full requirement—even though the edit distance algorithm itself could be tested in isolation at Unit level with mocks.\n\nActually, thinking through what failures matter: a Unit test with a mocked storage object can catch wrong computation, missing storage calls, and incorrect values being stored, all without needing a real database. So Unit is sufficient to verify the behavior works correctly.\n\nMinimum level: **Unit**\n\n**Behavior 5: When both translators are available, the service returns the primary translation and logs the quality comparison in the background.**\n\nThis involves multiple modules working together—the primary translator, fallback translator, quality tracking, and background logging—so it's an integration concern. I don't need real network calls since I can stub both translators with canned responses. The key question is whether the test depends on actual LLM output. The behavior is really about service orchestration: does it return the primary translation instead of the fallback, and does it trigger background logging? That's about routing logic, not translation quality, so a stubbed primary translator is enough to verify the service does the right thing.\n\nMocking won't hide failures here—stubs for both translators plus verification that background logging was called would catch any routing mistakes. Looking at the integration checklist: I don't need real OS or network calls, the assertion is about routing not translation quality so stubs work fine, there's no multi-step agentic behavior, and the routing decision is deterministic (primary available means use primary), not dependent on LLM judgment. The correctness hinges on the routing logic, not on what the translation actually says, so this isn't agentic.\n\nThis needs **Integration** level testing because multiple components—the primary translator client, fallback translator, quality tracker, and background task runner—have to work together. Now I'm compiling my final test level assignments across all five behaviors: translation quality needs agentic testing with real models, error handling and fallback routing is integration with stubs, SQLite lookup is integration with an in-memory database, edit distance is unit since it's a pure function, and service routing logic is integration with stubbed translators. Let me double-check behavior 4 about the edit distance computation.\n\nThe behavior requires both computing the edit distance and storing the metric. If I test this at unit level with mocked storage, I can verify the computation and confirm the storage call happens with the right value. But if the storage actually writes to SQLite, then mocking would miss bugs in the SQL query or database integration itself. Since the system description mentions SQLite for the fallback dictionary, it's reasonable to assume metrics might also go to SQLite or similar persistent storage. That means **Integration** is the right level for behavior 4 to catch real storage bugs. Hmm, but edit distance computation is the \"interesting\" part algorithmically. The storage is straightforward. Let me think about which failure mode is harder to catch...\n\nIf the edit distance algorithm is wrong, a Unit test catches it. If the storage is wrong (wrong table, wrong column, wrong query), an Integration test catches it. Since the behavior explicitly includes both, and the storage part genuinely needs Integration to be tested properly, I'll say **Integration**.\n\nActually, I keep going back and forth. Let me just decide:\n- The behavior explicitly includes \"stores the metric\"\n- Storage to SQLite (likely) requires real SQLite to test properly  \n- Therefore: **Integration**\n\nWait, for behavior 4, let me reconsider. The edit distance computation is a pure function that's clearly Unit-testable, and if the storage interface is well-defined, I can verify the correct value gets passed to storage using a mock at the Unit level. Integration testing would only add value if I need to verify actual SQL execution or database state. Since the storage implementation is likely simple, a mock/spy should be sufficient.\n\nFinal answers:\n1. Agentic\n2. Integration\n3. Integration\n4. Unit\n5. Integration\n\nNow I'm assigning probability distributions across test levels for each behavior. For behavior 1, translation quality absolutely requires a real neural MT model, so Agentic gets the highest probability at 0.85, with minimal probability elsewhere. For behavior 2, the error handling and fallback wiring is best tested at Integration level with a stubbed 503 response and real fallback logic, so that gets 0.75, though Unit testing the error handling logic alone could catch some issues.\n\nBehavior 3 is about database lookups—real SQLite is needed to verify query correctness, making Integration the strongest test level at 0.8, while mocking the database at Unit level would miss actual query bugs. For behavior 4, the edit distance calculation is a pure function that can be verified with mocks, so Unit testing gets the highest probability at 0.65, though if the storage layer uses real SQLite, Integration testing becomes more relevant at 0.3.\n\nNow looking at behavior 5, which involves multiple translator modules working together—I need real integration between them to catch wiring issues, so Integration testing is strongest at 0.75, though there's an argument for some Agentic testing at 0.08 if I need to verify the model actually identifies \"primary\" quality correctly. The key question is whether my test descriptions actually match the minimum test level I've assigned to each behavior, so I should make sure each test is written at the appropriate depth.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10147,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10147},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c0db2478-d3e1-480e-a6c4-a6b071f37658","uuid":"8194aa86-e872-4591-93d0-fcc70c461523"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_016wwQES8iqkFu6qwBv54nLF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KznJGbwa7oX4cPVZpnKpDj","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The primary translator produces a grammatically coherent translation that preserves the meaning of the source text, not just a word-for-word substitution.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: This behavior directly asserts on translation quality — grammatical coherence and meaning preservation. These properties only exist in real neural MT model output. A stub or mock always returns a constant string, so it can never reveal whether the model actually produces coherent, meaning-preserving translations vs. word-for-word substitutions. This is the canonical Agentic case: the correctness criterion is defined by AI/ML model output quality, not by deterministic logic around the model. REJECTION-GATE: No behavior text disqualifies Agentic — the behavior explicitly tests output quality ('grammatically coherent', 'preserves the meaning'), not infrastructure routing or retries.","test_description":"Submit a set of diverse source sentences (idiomatic expressions, compound structures, negations) to the real neural MT API and assert that each returned translation passes both a grammatical acceptability check and a semantic similarity threshold (e.g., cosine similarity against a reference translation ≥ 0.85, or manual review spot-check). Failures must be reproducible by re-running against the real model, not a stub.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.87,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the translation API returns a 503 error, the service transparently falls back to the dictionary-based translator without returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justifi